Sex Variables and Societal Equality

The first questions that interests us is whether or not individuals who took the survey as a whole believe that society treats men or women equally, men over women, or women over men. This question is “q4” in our data.

V1 <- EGW%>%group_by(q4) %>% summarise(count=length(q4))
head(V1)
## # A tibble: 4 × 2
##      q4 count
##   <dbl> <int>
## 1     1   780
## 2     2   174
## 3     3   924
## 4     9   124

Now that we have grouped the data to show how many answers there were for each question, lets change the numerical identifiers (1,2,3,and 9) into factoral questions such as “Equally,” “Women,” “Men,” and “Don’t know/Refuse.”

V1$q4<-recode(V1$q4,"'1'='Equally'")
V1$q4<-recode(V1$q4,"'2'='Women'")
V1$q4<-recode(V1$q4,"'3'='Men'")
V1$q4<-recode(V1$q4,"'9'='NA'")
head(V1)
## # A tibble: 4 × 2
##        q4 count
##     <chr> <int>
## 1 Equally   780
## 2   Women   174
## 3     Men   924
## 4      NA   124

Now that the labels are written out, it is much easier to clearly see how many individuals chose which option for the questions on who society treats better. Lets graph this newly altered data.

ggplot(V1, aes(x=q4,y=count, fill=q4)) +
geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
labs(title = "Precieved Societal Equallity", y = "Total", x = "Categories", fill="Categories")

This is very interesting information, however a deeper question is present within the data. What factors may influence ones opinion on societies treatment of men and women? Is sex a factor to who you think society favors?

Exploring Deeper

Before we begin our analysis, lets make sure we keep the variable names we created and apply it to our main dataset, EGW. While we are at it, lets change the sex to also indicate either male or female.

EGW$q4<-recode(EGW$q4,"'1'='Equally'")
EGW$q4<-recode(EGW$q4,"'2'='Women'")
EGW$q4<-recode(EGW$q4,"'3'='Men'")
EGW$q4<-recode(EGW$q4,"'9'='NA'")

EGW$sex<-recode(EGW$sex, "'1'='Male'")
EGW$sex<-recode(EGW$sex, "'2'='Female'")

Now lets see if one’s sex is a strong determinant as to whether or not they think men or women are treated better. We first group this data into a new subset called “V2.”

V2 <- EGW%>%group_by(q4, sex)

Now that we have grouped the data by sex and the question we are interested in, let us create a visual from this and see if our question can be answered any further.

ggplot(V2, aes(x=sex, fill=q4)) +
geom_bar(stat = "count", position="dodge") +
labs(title = "Male vs Female Perception", y = "Total", x = "Sex", fill="Categories")

From this visual, we can see that more females are likely to answer that men are treated greater in society. We also see that men have a higher tendency to answer that both sexes are treated equally when asked the same question. Females had a higher likelyhood of not responding to the question than responding with females being treated higher in society.

EGW$relig<-recode(EGW$relig,"'1'='Protestant'")

ggplot(V3, aes(x=relig, fill=q4)) +

As you can see our visualization is rather messy. We can manually reorder this data and try to graph this again. Lets order this in terms of how many participants there were. From this visual it is really hard to see how many individuals were in each religious group. In order to manually group them in order, we can use the table function to see what order we need to place them in.

table(V3$relig)
## 
##           Agnostic            Atheist           Buddhist 
##                 78                 80                 19 
##          Christian Does not identifty  Dont Know/Refused 
##                235                349                 17 
##              Hindu             Jewish             Mormon 
##                 14                 29                 45 
##             Muslim           Orthodox         Protestant 
##                 22                 12                720 
##     Roman Catholic     Something else          Unitarian 
##                354                 25                  3

As you can see, the proper order is as follows: Protestant, Roman Catholic, Does not identify, Christian, Atheist, Agnostic, Mormon, Jewish, Something else, Muslim, Buddhist, Dont Know/Refuse, Hindu, Orthodox, and Unitarian. We will now manually reorder our list to represent this sample size.

V3$relig <- factor(V3$relig,levels(V3$relig)[c(12,13,5,4,2,1,9,8,14,10,3,6,7,11,15)])

Now that we have reordered our religions, let us regraph our data.

ggplot(V3, aes(x=relig, fill=q4)) +
geom_bar(stat = "count", position="dodge") +
labs(title = "Religious Perception", y = "Total", x = "Religion", fill="Categories") + coord_flip()

With this new visual, we can see a few things very clearly. First off, our largest participating group is protestant participants, followed by the Roman Catholics, those who do not want to identify and finally Christians. Second, we can see that no group as a whole believes that women are more favorable than men in society or that women are more favorable than an equal society. Only five groups believed that society treated both groups equally more than men. Within these five groups, two of them were those who refused to answer and those who identified as something else. For the sake of looking specifically at religious groups and their perception on society’s treatment of men and women, we will look at the other three groups, Roman Catholics, Muslim, and Hindus, more closely.

Sex and Religous Variables and Societal Equality

We will be taking a closer look at all three of the religions we have identified and see what portion of Females made up the answers provided. If Roman Catholic for example consisted of only men who chose the “equally” option and simply were a greater sample size then men, this could be misleading.

First let us look at the Roman Catholic distribution individualy.

ggplot(V3, aes(relig, fill=q4)) + geom_bar(data=subset(V3,relig=="Roman Catholic"),stat="count", position="dodge")+
  labs(title = "Roman Catholic Perception", y = "Total", x = "Religion", fill="Categories")

We can see from this visual that Roman Catholic participants favored equaly as an option over Men very slightly. Within the Roman Catholic group, it would be interesting to see how many Roman Catholic men chose the equally choice over women.

ggplot(V3, aes(x=sex, fill=q4)) +
geom_bar(data=subset(V3,relig=="Roman Catholic"),stat = "count", position="dodge") +
labs(title = "Roman Catholic Male vs Female Perception", y = "Total", x = "Sex", fill="Categories")

The interesting thing to note in this case is that it was a majority of males within the Roman Catholic participant group, and not the females, who chose the equally option. Most women believed that men were suprior in society while most men believe that men and women were equals to eachother.

Next let us look at teh Muslim distribution individualy.

ggplot(V3, aes(relig, fill=q4)) + geom_bar(data=subset(V3,relig=="Muslim"),stat="count", position="dodge")+
  labs(title = "Muslin Perception", y = "Total", x = "Religion", fill="Categories")

It is interesting in this case to see that Muslim participants where almost twice as likely to select equally as an option over men. Though this result is suprising, we can look again at the male and female distributions of the Muslim paticipants.

ggplot(V3, aes(x=sex, fill=q4)) +
geom_bar(data=subset(V3,relig=="Muslim"),stat = "count", position="dodge") +
labs(title = "Muslim Male vs Female Perception", y = "Total", x = "Sex", fill="Categories")

In this case we can see two things that are unique. First, the number of male muslim participants of the survey more than double those of female muslim participants. Second however, we see that despite this, female muslim participants of the survey were more likely to say that society treated men and women equally over favoring men. This is suprising so far, but we can still look at the Hundu data individualy as well.

ggplot(V3, aes(relig, fill=q4)) + geom_bar(data=subset(V3,relig=="Hindu"),stat="count", position="dodge")+
  labs(title = "Hindu Perception", y = "Total", x = "Religion", fill="Categories")

For the Hindu data, it is not quite as extreme as the Muslim data, but it does show that equally was selected by the Hindu participants much more often then the men option was selected. Again we will go one step deeper and see the male and female difference within the Hindu data set.

ggplot(V3, aes(x=sex, fill=q4)) +
geom_bar(data=subset(V3,relig=="Hindu"),stat = "count", position="dodge") +
labs(title = "Hindu Male vs Female Perception", y = "Total", x = "Sex", fill="Categories")

Female Hindu participants were just as likely to select equally or men as their answer when participating in the survey. Men on the other hand were twice as likely to select equally over the men option when answering the survey.

From this analysis of the three religions, we can see a flaw in our analysis. If we do not seperate the male and female particpants before looking at the religious factors regarding societal equality, we could assume a false result. All three of the religions we just looked at overall said that society treated men and women equally, however Roman Catholic females were not likely to respond this way at all. Muslim Females on the other hand were more likely to respond this way.

In order to create a more focused analysis, we will exclude men from our analysis and look at what factors may be involved in women choosing “Equally” as a response to q4 over choosing “Men”.

Isolating Females in our Data

We will now be isolating our data to only females who decided to respond either “Equally” or “Men” for question q4 so that we can better understand the possible factors that might cause someone to respond differently from the appartant norm. The six factors we will be looking at that might affect this decision are as follows:

q1 - The general happiness q2a - Family life satisfaction q2b - Financial satisfaction educ2 - Level of education qe3 - Employment status relig - Religion age - Age

To make our analysis easier, we will create a subset of data of only female particpants who answered “Equally” and female participants who answered “Men” for q4. For this first subset, lets create a group of all females.

Females <- subset(EGW, sex == "Female", 
select=c(q1,q2a,q2b,educ2,qe3,relig,age,q4))

MP <- subset(Females, q4 == "Equally" | q4 == "Men",

Conclusion

In our analysis we tried to analyse the factors that might cause a Female participant to respond that Men and Women are treated equally in society over the most common answer, that Men are favored over Women in society.

Through our analysis, we discoved that both the factors of age and employment status of the participant are low, if not completely unrelated, to their view on societal equality.

Females who answered that they thought men and women were treated equally in society tended to be happier in their life, in their family, and in their finances.

Muslim women and those women who refused to answer about their religion had the highest chance of selecting equally when asked about societal equality.

There was a slight trend that those who answered that society treated men and women equally had a lower level of education compared to those who said than men were favored in society.

There were no profound difference in any of the questions analyzed between the two groups. In future analysis of this data, it would be interesting to compare those who answered “Women” and those who answered “Men” in the question regarding societal equality.
